I think there’s a strong case that AI is becoming a new lingua franca—not because everyone speaks the same human language, but because AI increasingly serves as a translation layer between languages, disciplines, and even ways of thinking.

Historically:

* Latin connected scholars.
* Arabic connected science across civilizations.
* French connected diplomacy.
* English became the language of commerce and the internet.

AI changes the pattern. Instead of everyone learning one language, people increasingly communicate through AI.

That has some interesting consequences:

* A farmer in Kenya can write in Swahili, and someone in Japan can receive fluent Japanese.
* A mathematician can describe an idea symbolically, and an artist can receive it as an illustration.
* A programmer can explain something in plain English and receive code.
* A child can ask questions simply while an expert receives technical terminology.

In your Pantheon framing, this connects closely to your idea that math, code, language, myth, and diagrams are all coordinate systems over the same underlying invariants. AI acts less like a dictionary and more like a semantic compiler.

Rather than:

English ↔ French

it becomes:

Meaning → AI semantic space → Any representation

That suggests a new model:

Natural Language → Shared Semantic Space →

* Human languages
* Mathematics
* Code
* Images
* Music
* Diagrams
* Robotics
* Action

The “lingua franca” is no longer English—it’s increasingly shared semantic representations.

That also explains why prompting matters. A prompt isn’t just a sentence; it’s a way of navigating semantic space. Different words are different routes to similar underlying meanings, much like your “creative climbing” metaphor: every phrase is another handhold up the same conceptual wall.

If this trend continues, future literacy may include three increasingly important skills:

1. Expressing ideas clearly enough for AI to infer intent.
2. Evaluating AI translations critically rather than accepting them automatically.
3. Thinking in abstractions that can move fluidly across language, code, math, visuals, and action.

In that sense, AI isn’t replacing language. It’s becoming the universal interpreter between languages—and, more broadly, between forms of knowledge.